    Highlights

    •
    KARMA, an approach to characterize maturation and dynamics of protein complexes
    •
    Metabolic labeling rates reveal complex maturation time and assembly order
    •
    Nuclear pore complex maturation follows a modular principle
    •
    Nucleoporins assemble from center to periphery on a minute to hour timescale

    Summary

    All proteins interact with other cellular components to fulfill their function. While tremendous progress has been made in the identification of protein complexes, their assembly and dynamics remain difficult to characterize. Here, we present a high-throughput strategy to analyze the native assembly kinetics of protein complexes. We apply our approach to characterize the co-assembly for 320 pairs of nucleoporins (NUPs) constituting the ≈50 MDa nuclear pore complex (NPC) in yeast. Some NUPs co-assemble fast via rapid exchange whereas others require lengthy maturation steps. This reveals a hierarchical principle of NPC biogenesis where individual subcomplexes form on a minute timescale and then co-assemble from center to periphery in a ∼1 h-long maturation process. Intriguingly, the NUP Mlp1 stands out as joining very late and associating preferentially with aged NPCs. Our approach is readily applicable beyond the NPC, making it possible to analyze the intracellular dynamics of a variety of multiprotein assemblies.

    To characterize the native assembly process of multiprotein complexes, we introduce here a method, entitled kinetic analysis of incorporation rates in macromolecular assemblies (KARMA). In KARMA, the co-assembly of newly synthesized proteins into a final complex is analyzed akin to a metabolic process by observing metabolic labeling kinetics in affinity-isolated protein complexes. We applied KARMA to study the process of NPC biogenesis and evaluated co-assembly kinetics among 320 pairs of NUPs in actively growing yeast cells. Based on that, we mapped the native order and timing of NPC biogenesis. We find that NUPs initially form subcomplexes, which then assemble in a hierarchical way from the center to the periphery. Unexpectedly, individual NUPs progress through the NPC maturation process at drastically different rates, ranging from minutes to ∼1 h, and incorporate into NPCs by different mechanisms: some via dynamic exchange and others by transiting through time-consuming maturation stages. Our results uncover central principles of NPC biogenesis and demonstrate the general utility of metabolic labeling to characterize the dynamics of macromolecular complexes.

    Results

    Principle of KARMA

    Protein complex formation can be thought of as a metabolic process. It begins with the synthesis of new proteins from smaller blocks (amino acids) and proceeds via a chain of maturation intermediates that include folding and multi-subunit assembly steps, ultimately resulting in a mature complex (Figure 1A). In our approach to probe the maturation processes of multiprotein complexes (KARMA), one of the protein components of the target complex (the “bait”) is affinity tagged, and newly synthesized proteins are pulse-labeled in actively growing cells by stable isotope labeling using amino acids in cell culture (SILAC) (Ong et al., 2002
    51.
    Ong, S.E. ∙ Blagoev, B. ∙ Kratchmarova, I. ...
    Stable isotope labeling by amino acids in cell culture, SILAC, as a simple and accurate approach to expression proteomics
    Mol. Cell. Proteomics. 2002; 1:376-386
    Full Text
    Full Text (PDF)
    Scopus (4754)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ). The tagged protein is isolated by an affinity pull-down (AP) procedure at several post-labeling time points, enabling the detection of bound complex components (the “preys”) (Figure 1A). For each time point, the isolated complexes are assayed by data-independent acquisition (DIA) mass spectrometry (Gillet et al., 2012
    24.
    Gillet, L.C. ∙ Navarro, P. ∙ Tate, S. ...
    Targeted data extraction of the MS/MS spectra generated by data-independent acquisition: a new concept for consistent and accurate proteome analysis
    Mol Cell Proteomics. 2012; 11
    O111.016717
    Full Text
    Full Text (PDF)
    Scopus (2069)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ) to compute the extent of isotopic protein labeling for each prey (Figures 1B, 1C, and S1A).
    The appearance of an isotopic label in prey proteins is inevitably delayed due to preceding structural maturation events (Figure 1A). To provide a quantitative framework that relates the labeling kinetics observed in KARMA to assembly events during the maturation process, we developed a simple kinetic state model (KSM) analogous to models used to analyze metabolic fluxes (Niedenführ et al., 2015
    46.
    Niedenführ, S. ∙ Wiechert, W. ∙ Nöh, K.
    How to measure metabolic fluxes: a taxonomic guide for (13)C fluxomics
    Curr. Opin. Biotechnol. 2015; 34:82-90
    Crossref
    Scopus (100)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ) and incorporation of proteins into a bacterial ribosome (Chen et al., 2012
    13.
    Chen, S.S. ∙ Sperling, E. ∙ Silverman, J.M. ...
    Measuring the dynamics of E. coli ribosome biogenesis using pulse-labeling and quantitative mass spectrometry
    Mol. Biosyst. 2012; 8:3325-3334
    Crossref
    Scopus (41)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ). Our KSM describes the propagation of isotopically labeled amino acids throughout the maturation of a protein complex in a growing cell culture as they incorporate into a complex together with a prey protein and are carried along distinct maturation states (Figure 1). In the simplest scenario, the amino acids transition from a maturation state (S1), where the newly made prey protein folds or binds to other components, to the mature state (S2), which is reached when the prey co-assembles with the affinity bait, producing the final KARMA readout as analyzed by AP followed by mass spectrometry (Figures 1A, 1D, and 1E; STAR Methods, “Irreversible 2-step assembly”). Other contributing factors such as prey dynamic exchange, degradation, or amino acid turnover can be accounted for by introducing additional KSM states and fluxes (Figures 2F and S4; STAR Methods).
    In our simple KSM, the distribution between the two states determines the timing of prey labeling, where a higher fraction of protein present in the maturation state translates to slower labeling (Figures 1E, S4A, and S4B) (STAR Methods, “Irreversible 2-step assembly”). The same also holds true for proteins that can reversibly detach and dynamically exchange between complexes. The labeling kinetics of such proteins can be represented by adding reverse flux to the KSM and mimic stably bound proteins albeit with a smaller fraction in the maturation state (Figure 2F). By fitting KARMA readouts with the KSM for non-dynamic proteins, we can quantify the effective fraction of protein in the maturation state, which we refer to as EMP (effective maturation pool), taking values between 0 and 1. For stably bound proteins, the EMP would be an unbiased estimate of the real fraction of protein in the maturation state. For dynamic proteins with an off-rate of 𝐾off, however, the EMP would underestimate the real fraction by a constant factor of (1+𝐾off/𝜇)−1, where μ is the cell culture growth rate (STAR Methods, “2-step assembly with reversibility”).
    When KARMA assays are performed with different structural components of a complex as affinity baits, we expect to observe a larger EMP whenever a bait is located further downstream of a given prey in an ordered maturation process (Figure 3A). Thus, by providing an estimate of the protein fraction in the maturation state, the EMP gives a relative measure for the length of the maturation process for a given prey protein with respect to different baits, where more downstream baits will give rise to higher EMPs (Figure 3A). Such kinetic readouts provide proximity measures for multiple bait-prey pairs in the maturation process and, therefore, can be used to delineate the order and timing of structural biogenesis events (Figure 5A).

    Applying KARMA to Analyze the Biogenesis of the Yeast NPC

    In budding yeast, the NPC has a mass of approximately 50 MDa and comprises a total of ∼500 proteins (Kim et al., 2018

They form the major NPC sub-structures: two outer rings and the inner ring complex (IRC), which is anchored to the membrane ring and connects to the cytoplasmic export platform, the central channel, and the nuclear basket (Figure 2A).
    To test the feasibility of KARMA for the analysis of NPC biogenesis, we initially monitored the labeling kinetics of Mlp1, a nuclear basket NUP and well-established affinity bait for the isolation of structurally intact NPCs (Kim et al., 2018
    34.
    Kim, S.J. ∙ Fernandez-Martinez, J. ∙ Nudelman, I. ...
    Integrative structure and functional anatomy of a nuclear pore complex
    Nature. 2018; 555:475-482
    Crossref
    Scopus (345)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ). Mlp1 was endogenously tagged with a tandem Z domain of staphylococcal protein A (ZZ tag) in haploid yeast cells deficient in lysine biosynthesis (Oeffinger et al., 2007
    50.
    Oeffinger, M. ∙ Wei, K.E. ∙ Rogers, R. ...
    Comprehensive analysis of diverse ribonucleoprotein complexes
    Nat. Methods. 2007; 4:951-956
    Crossref
    Scopus (217)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ; de Godoy, 2014
    16.
    de Godoy, L.M.
    SILAC yeast: from labeling to comprehensive proteome quantification
    Methods Mol. Biol. 2014; 1156:81-109
    Crossref
    Scopus (10)
    PubMed

    ). Newly produced proteins were pulse-labeled in a log-phase culture by quickly exchanging the light lysine synthetic medium with a medium containing 13C6 15N2 (heavy) lysine. Culture samples were collected both immediately before labeling onset and at 30 min intervals thereafter, followed by ZZ-tag APs and mass-spectrometric analysis (Figures 1B and S1A).
    We were able to consistently detect and quantify the labeling of 32 NUPs (i.e., all NUPs except for Nup42 and Pom33) across five time points along with more than 600 co-isolated yeast proteins (Figure S1B). NUP labeling was highly reproducible across three biological replicates (Figure S1C; Table S4; see Mendeley data in Data and Code Availability). NUPs were, on average, labeled more slowly than co-purified bulk proteins and strictly slower than the Mlp1 bait (Figure 2C; Table S4), consistent with them undergoing a maturation process.
    At the same time, we found that NUP labeling rates showed a high degree of variability. NUPs of the symmetrical core, membrane ring, and central channel were generally labeled at slower rates than the ones from the nuclear basket and cytoplasmic export platform. Although labeling rates within sub-structures were typically similar, there were striking exceptions. Within the membrane ring, Ndc1 was labeled with heavy lysine much faster than Pom34 and Pom152. Furthermore, Nup82 and Nup159 of the cytoplasmic export platform were labeled slower than the other components (Figure 2B; Table S4). Another notable case was Nup145N and Nup145C: these two proteins are produced by autoproteolytic cleavage of a single precursor polypeptide, directly bind to one another (Teixeira et al., 1997
    68.
    Teixeira, M.T. ∙ Siniossoglou, S. ∙ Podtelejnikov, S. ...
    Two functionally distinct domains generated by in vivo cleavage of Nup145p: a novel biogenesis pathway for nucleoporins
    EMBO J. 1997; 16:5086-5097
    Crossref
    Scopus (89)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ; Ratner et al., 2007
    61.
    Ratner, G.A. ∙ Hodel, A.E. ∙ Powers, M.A.
    Molecular determinants of binding between Gly-Leu-Phe-Gly nucleoporins and the nuclear pore complex
    J. Biol. Chem. 2007; 282:33968-33976
    Full Text
    Full Text (PDF)
    Scopus (17)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ) and yet display significantly different labeling kinetics (Figure 2D; Table S4). Unlike NUPs, nuclear transport receptors (NTRs), which associate with the NPC in a highly dynamic manner, were all rapidly labeled at a rate similar to the Mlp1 bait (Figure 2B; Table S4).
    To test whether the diverse NUP labeling rates could arise from in vitro intermixing during the AP procedure, we analyzed the labeling kinetics of proteins after mixing cell extracts from unlabeled Mlp1-ZZ tagged cultures with wild-type cultures that were labeled with heavy lysine (Figure S1D). In contrast to the highly dynamic NTRs, NUPs displayed low intermixing (<10% labeling), demonstrating that post-lysis intermixing is not a major contributor to our KARMA readouts (Figure S1E; Table S4).
    Enhanced labeling kinetics could also be due to differences in protein turnover rates (STAR Methods, “Irreversible 2-step assembly with degradation”). Although earlier proteome-wide analyses had shown that NUPs and NTRs are stable proteins with very slow turnover (Christiano et al., 2014
    14.
    Christiano, R. ∙ Nagaraj, N. ∙ Fröhlich, F. ...
    Global proteome turnover analyses of the Yeasts S. cerevisiae and S. pombe
    Cell Rep. 2014; 9:1959-1965
    Full Text
    Full Text (PDF)
    Scopus (192)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ), it was important to evaluate whether the diversity in labeling rates could be explained by this factor. To this end, we compared the labeling of NUPs, NTRs, and other abundant proteins co-purified in KARMA to the labeling in total cell lysates, which were the source for the respective APs. Parallel reaction monitoring (Peterson et al., 2012

We therefore conclude that total intracellular pools of these proteins are replenished at similar rates and that any labeling delay observed in KARMA can be confidently explained by the non-equal time it takes for different NUPs to assemble into a complex with Mlp1.
    The observed labeling differences are well explained by our KSM as a tug of war between two kinetic factors: (1) a labeling delay caused by maturation steps preceding the co-assembly with Mlp1 and (2) an accelerating effect caused by a protein’s dynamic exchange that effectively reduces the maturation pool size to various extents for different proteins (Figures 1E and 2F) (STAR Methods, “2-step assembly with reversibility”). The lack of a maturation state for the bait protein explains the similar labeling kinetics of Mlp1 in total cell lysates and APs (Figure 2E; Table S4). Furthermore, the exceptionally dynamic association of NTRs with the NPC, also observed in our intermixing assays (Figure S1E), effectively shrinks their EMPs to zero and leads to similar labeling kinetics in APs and total cell lysates (Figure 2E; Table S4).     Kinetic Parameters of NPC Maturation Events

    Having established that KARMA can detect differences in NUP maturation kinetics, we expanded our approach to use nine additional NUP baits representing all of the NPC sub-structures except for the membrane ring (Figures 2A and S2A). The Y complex was represented by Nup133, Nup84, and Nup85; the IRC by Nup188; the central channel by Nup57 and Nsp1; the cytoplasmic export platform by Nup82, Nup159, and Nsp1; and the nuclear basket by Nup1 and Mlp1 (Figure 2A). A strain expressing a plain ZZ-tag under the control of the Mlp1 promoter (mock bait) was used to discriminate between specific and non-specific interactors in the APs.
    In total, we analyzed 120 samples across three post-labeling time points (30, 60, and 90 min), which allowed us to determine the labeling kinetics of all NUPs except Nup42 and Pom33 (Figure S2B) along with ∼900 other proteins. NUPs were highly enriched in the APs with all baits compared to the mock control (Figures S2E and S2F) and displayed highly reproducible labeling across biological replicates (Figures S2C; Table S4; see also Mendeley data in Data and Code Availability). As seen for Mlp1, newly synthesized prey NUPs accumulated heavy lysine slower than their cognate baits (Figure S2D). NUP labeling significantly varied depending on the bait, in a striking contrast to the NTRs and the majority of other co-purifying proteins (Figure S2B). For example, the majority of Y complex preys were labeled significantly faster when probed with the Y complex members Nup85, Nup84, and Nup133 compared to other NUP baits. Similarly, labeling of the cytoplasmic export platform Nup82, Nup159, and Nsp1 was faster when the bait was a member of the same subcomplex (Figure S2B). Nsp1 was labeled faster with the Nup57 bait, consistent with it being a part of the central channel complex (Nsp1-Nup57-Nup49) (Figure S2B). This indicates that NPC maturation is an overall ordered process and that KARMA can be used to examine this order and its kinetics.
    To better characterize the process of NPC biogenesis, we next quantified the duration of the maturation events for each NUP from the moment of biosynthesis to its assembly with each of the 10 baits. As a measure, we determined the EMPs by fitting the KARMA readouts with the KSM for non-dynamic proteins (Figure S5A) (STAR Methods, “KSM for each bait/prey based on labeling”). In our KSM parameterization, we used the median labeling values of three NTRs (Kap95, Kap123, and Mex67) as internal references. These three reference proteins have low protein turnover rates (Christiano et al., 2014
    14.
    Christiano, R. ∙ Nagaraj, N. ∙ Fröhlich, F. ...

    ), were reliably detected in all of the KARMA assays, and exhibited consistent and similar labeling kinetics across APs and in total cell lysates (Figures 2E and S2B; Table S4; see Mendeley data in Data and Code Availability). Since the labeling of these proteins was not affected by NPC maturation, they could be used to specifically determine the contribution of the maturation process to the observed labeling kinetics of the preys. In our analysis, we also accounted for the turnover of the intracellular pool of lysine. During translation light lysine molecules that are available in the cell will compete with heavy lysine and thus globally “delay” the labeling of all new proteins including both preys and internal references. To examine and correct for the effect of the intracellular lysine pool on labeling kinetics, we compared the labeling patterns of single- and double-lysine peptides that originate from the same protein, which provide an accurate measure of the heavy lysine fraction available in cells. This enabled us to determine the turnover rate for the intracellular lysine pool and use it in KSM parametrizations when calculating the EMPs (Figures S4F–S4J and S5A; STAR Methods, “Estimating intracellular lysine turnover”). In contrast to the lysine content, the peptide position (N- or C-terminal) had no detectable effect on the labeling, indicating that translation does not significantly influence the labeling kinetics (see Mendeley data in Data and Code Availability). In a few cases, when protein labeling exceeded the reference values (likely due to the fact that mature structures were inaccessible in the APs), we extended the KSM to include an additional inaccessible state (Figures S4C–S4E and S5C; STAR Methods, “KSM for each bait/prey based on labeling”).
    Altogether, we could fit KARMA readouts and evaluate EMPs for 320 bait-prey pairs of NUPs that displayed a wide range between nearly zero and up to ∼80% (median 8%) (Figure 3B; Table S3; see also Mendeley data in Data and Code Availability).
    Interestingly, we noticed significant bait-dependent variability: EMPs obtained with the NUP baits belonging to the asymmetric NPC sub-structures were distinctively higher than with the symmetric core baits (highest Mlp1, median value 28.9%; lowest Nup133, median value 4.3%) (Figures 2A, 3C, and 3G). Since higher EMPs indicate later co-assembly with prey proteins (Figure 3A), this observation suggests that the asymmetric bait NUPs join the NPC maturation process at later steps than the symmetric core baits.
    We also observed striking prey-dependent differences among EMPs (Figure 3D). For Nsp1, Seh1, Nup188, and Nup133, the EMPs were overall elevated, and their maximum values exceeded 50% (Figure 3D; Table S3). Since these values represent conservative estimates for the protein fraction in the maturation state (STAR Methods, “2-step assembly with reversibility”), our analysis suggests that a relatively large fraction of newly made species of these proteins is not stably incorporated into the NPC at steady state.
    In our analyses, proteins that rapidly exchange at the NPC are expected to show low EMPs for all baits (STAR Methods, “2-step assembly with reversibility”). Distinctly low EMPs (maximum values ∼10%) were observed for the majority of linker and nuclear basket NUPs, including Nup145N, Nup116, Mlp2, Nup60, Nup2, and Nup1, pointing to their dynamic association with the NPC (Figures 2A and 3D; Table S3).     Our KSM framework also defines a temporal distance in the maturation process, which we refer to as the effective maturation time (𝐸⁢𝑀⁢𝑇=𝑡𝐷×𝜑′/(1−𝜑′), where 𝑡𝐷 is cell culture doubling time and 𝜑′ is the EMP; STAR Methods, “Analytical solution for maturation time”).     Altogether, our findings demonstrate that NPC biogenesis is a non-random and lengthy process that requires on average approximately one yeast cell cycle to be fully completed. NUPs take very different routes to join the NPC, and we can differentiate rapidly exchanging fast-maturing NUPs (like Ndc1, Nup60, and Nup2) from slow-maturing ones (such as Nup133, Nup188, Seh1, and Nsp1), which are likely present in large maturation pools not stably associated with the NPC structure.

    Identification of Co-assembling NUPs

    We next set out to determine the order of the NPC maturation events. NUPs that quickly interact after biosynthesis and stay together in a stable subcomplex should share the same downstream assembly intermediates and, as a result, are expected to produce highly correlated labeling patterns when probed with different baits (Figure 4A).
    We computed pairwise correlation distances among NUP labeling profiles at the first post-labeling time point (labeling values obtained across all ten baits) and subjected them to hierarchical clustering (Figure 4B). Using this analysis, NUPs could be divided into nine similarity groups, which were also largely conserved across all time points (Figures 4B–4D and S3A). The smallest groups contained only a single protein, such as Mlp1, Mlp2, and Nup188, whereas the largest group—the Nup53 group—comprised nine NUPs (Figures 4D). Ndc1 and Gle1 were not categorized since they did not show labeling similarity to any other NUPs likely due to highly dynamic behavior and high variability of labeling values among biological replicates, respectively (Figures 3D, 3J, S2B, and S3D). Another outlier was Nsp1, which is a component of both the central channel and the cytoplasmic export platform complex. Although it showed some labeling similarity to both the Nup159 and Nup57 groups at later time points (Figures S3A and S3C), it could not be exclusively assigned to any of the two.
    Consistent with a co-assembly behavior, the bait-prey pairs from the same group were much closer to one another in the maturation order and had drastically shorter EMTs compared to bait-prey pairs from other groups (median within-group EMT <1 min, median between-groups EMT ≈9 min) (Figures 3A, 4E, and 4F). Interestingly, for Seh1, a member of the Y complex, the shortest EMT exceeded 20 min. Thus, Seh1 likely undergoes a lengthy maturation process that delays its interactions with other NUPs (Figures 3E and S3F). Similarly, Mlp1 and Nup188 display large EMT values across all baits (Figures 3E and S3F).

    Global Order and Timescale of NPC Biogenesis

    The diverse maturation kinetics that we observed for bait-prey pairs from different assembly groups (Figures 4E and 4F) suggest that the higher-order NPC assembly follows an ordered pathway. To delineate this pathway, we developed an unbiased, computational pipeline in which NPC biogenesis was represented as a binary tree and assembly groups were allowed to merge until they form the complete NPC structure (Figures 5A and S5E; STAR Methods, “Maturation sequence of NPC biogenesis”). All possible binary trees were scored to find the best predictors producing the closest possible match to the observed EMP values (Figure 5A).
    Within each assembly group, we defined a single, representative bait and a set of non-bait proteins (Figure S5D). We excluded potentially dynamic proteins within each group (NUPs that displayed small EMPs with all baits) and, where applicable, NUPs that assemble within the group with a significant delay (e.g., Seh1). There were 2,027,025 possible binary trees with nine distinct leaves (Figure S5F; STAR Methods, “Tree generating procedure”). This number was small enough to perform an exhaustive search of all trees and to score them based on the root mean square error (RMSE) to the experimentally obtained EMPs for the respective bait-prey pairs (Figure 5A; STAR Methods, “KSM for each bait/prey based on labeling”).
    Our analysis did not reveal a prominent single best fit, but among the best trees, we found many with almost identical scores (Figure S5F; see Mendeley data in Data and Code Availability). In order to avoid over-fitting, we pooled the 0.1% highest ranking trees and identified the maturation order from the distributions of the levels for each group, representing the number of merges required to assemble into a complete structure (Figures 5A–5C). Based on that, the assembly groups could be split into three distinct tiers with highly similar positions in the maturation order. An early tier (highest levels) contained the Nup53, Nup188, Nup57, and Nup84 groups comprising the symmetrical NPC elements as well as Nup116 and Gle2; the intermediate tier contained the asymmetrical NUPs (the Nup159 group and Nup1 group) and, interestingly, also the head part of the Y complex (Nup85 group). The late tier was represented by Mlp1 and Mlp2, which were observed to associate last (Figures 5B–5D). Of note, similar results were also obtained with the EMP values corrected for protein intermixing at the AP step (Figures S5H and S5I; Table S4; see Mendeley data in Data and Code Availability; STAR Methods, “Contribution of AP intermixing”), indicating that our NPC maturation model is sufficiently robust against this bias. Taken together, NPC maturation begins with the symmetric NUPs, continues with the asymmetric ones, and concludes with the Mlp proteins.
    To approximate the timescale of these milestone events, we also determined median maturation times for pairs of NUPs across tiers. Whereas both early and intermediate tier NUPs co-assemble into one complex relatively quickly (with maturation times of ∼10 min and ∼5 min, respectively), their final assembly with the late tier occurs on a remarkably long timescale with a maturation time of ∼1 h (Figures 5D and S5G).
    Our results suggested that Mlp1 and Mlp2 preferentially bind to morphologically complete NPC structures ∼1 h after their formation. To confirm this unexpected finding, we again used RITE and visualized new and old NPCs in live cells either by removing or introducing a GFP-tag at the C terminus of the early tier NUP Nup133 (Figure 6A). Remarkably, mCherry-tagged Mlp1 co-localized very well with old NPCs but not with new NPC structures (Figures 6B–6E). We observed this both using NE cross-correlation between GFP and mCherry signals (Figures 6B and 6C) and by examining individual NPCs at mitotic anaphase bridges (Rajoo et al., 2018

    Discussion

    Protein complexes are at the heart of most cellular processes (Hartwell et al., 1999

    Hartwell, L.H. ∙ Hopfield, J.J. ∙ Leibler, S. ...

In this study, we introduce KARMA, which characterizes the order and assembly kinetics of protein complexes similar to methods used for analyzing metabolic processes (Cheah and Young, 2018

    ).
    Current methods used to analyze the native assembly of macromolecular complexes are generally structure-centered: individual assembly intermediates are either identified in situ, in cell extracts, or biochemically isolated and characterized to compare their subunit composition and infer the assembly order (Harnpicharnchai et al., 2001
    26.
    Harnpicharnchai, P. ∙ Jakovljevic, J. ∙ Horsey, E. ...

    Chen, S.S. ∙ Sperling, E. ∙ Silverman, J.M. ...
    Measuring the dynamics of E. coli ribosome biogenesis using pulse-labeling and quantitative mass spectrometry
    Mol. Biosyst. 2012; 8:3325-3334
    Crossref
    Scopus (41)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ; Bogenhagen et al., 2018
    8.
    Bogenhagen, D.F. ∙ Ostermeyer-Fay, A.G. ∙ Haley, J.D. ...
    Kinetics and Mechanism of Mammalian Mitochondrial Ribosome Assembly
    Cell Rep. 2018; 22:1935-1944

    ). By contrast, KARMA presents a bottom-up approach to this problem. Similarities and differences in co-assembly kinetics of baits and preys are used to delineate the order and timing of the complex maturation process. Importantly, every bait in KARMA represents an independent experiment. This renders KARMA readily applicable to structures with a wide range of complexities and abundances. Moreover, a priori knowledge of complex composition is not a prerequisite; the information on protein interactions can be obtained directly from the experiments by analyzing specific enrichments. In addition, the generated mass-spectrometry data can detect other maturation events, e.g., changes in post-translational modifications or polypeptide integrity.
    The quantitative framework of KARMA is a KSM (Figures 1, S4, and S5). Our KSM is an implementation of an isotopically instationary steady-state metabolic flux analysis (INST-MFA)—a variant of metabolic flux analysis developed to quantify the rates of enzyme-catalyzed reactions in the cell using isotopic labeling of small molecules. The ordinary differential equation system at the root of INST-MFA is the basis for our KSM, which extends it beyond pure metabolic networks into the realm of protein synthesis and maturation. Previously, such an approach was already used to characterize the maturation process of E. coli ribosomes (Chen et al., 2012
    13.
    Chen, S.S. ∙ Sperling, E. ∙ Silverman, J.M. ...
    Measuring the dynamics of E. coli ribosome biogenesis using pulse-labeling and quantitative mass spectrometry
    Mol. Biosyst. 2012; 8:3325-3334
    Crossref
    Scopus (41)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ).
    The protein labeling data used in KARMA to characterize maturation processes are influenced by other factors besides the maturation per se. This includes variability, e.g., in time of sample collection, growth rate difference among strains, potential differences in the protein biosynthesis (translation) rates, or protein turnover. To account for the contribution of these factors, we relied on internal references in our analysis. One important internal reference is provided by proteins whose labeling kinetics are not affected by the maturation of the complex of interest. In the present work we used NTRs—a protein group known to highly dynamically interact with the NPC (Aramburu and Lemke, 2017
    3.
    Aramburu, I.V. ∙ Lemke, E.A.
    Floppy but not sloppy: Interaction mechanism of FG-nucleoporins and nuclear transport receptors
    Semin. Cell Dev. Biol. 2017; 68:34-41
    Crossref
    Scopus (68)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ). The only general requirements for such internal references are a low turnover rate, as well as similar labeling rates across different baits and in total cell lysates versus APs. These references can be easily chosen among the multitude of co-purified proteins. Additionally, we accounted for an inaccessible pool of proteins by introducing an inaccessible state into our KSM as well as for the available lysine pool in yeast cells monitoring differences in labeling between single- and double-lysine peptides (Figures S4F–S4J). In fact, our estimated turnover of the intracellular lysine pool is only about three times faster than the duration of the yeast cell cycle, and therefore lysine turnover significantly and globally delays protein labeling. Large cellular amounts of lysine could be contributed by protein turnover including co-translational protein degradation (Turner and Varshavsky, 2000
    72.
    Turner, G.C. ∙ Varshavsky, A.
    Detecting and measuring cotranslational protein degradation in vivo
    Science. 2000; 289:2117-2120
    Crossref
    Scopus (205)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ). We note that this factor is often not accounted for in pulse-labeling experiments but can lead to a significant bias in estimated rates and pool sizes.
    Our KSM-based analysis readily identifies dynamic proteins within target structures. Using the KSM framework, we demonstrate that the EMP is sensitive to exchange (STAR Methods, “2-step assembly with reversibility”). As a result, a low EMP, regardless of the bait, is a signature of proteins that rapidly exchange between bound and unbound states.     The basis of modern molecular biology lies in classic experiments, e.g., the demonstration of the chemical nature of genes (Hershey and Chase, 1952
    28.
    Hershey, A.D. ∙ Chase, M.

    ). These foundational studies were carried out by metabolic labeling, harnessing the interconversion of small cellular metabolites to trace the fate of vital macromolecules. Conceptually, KARMA builds on these classic approaches. The metabolite in our analysis is heavy lysine, while the macromolecular actors are distinct proteins that have a defined origin (protein synthesis) and a defined destination (complex with another protein of interest). By employing a modern quantitative framework, we quantify distances between these two points to evaluate the dynamics of protein-protein interactions. Although here we apply KARMA to a single structure, the NPC, this platform can easily be adapted to uncover other currently enigmatic dynamic aspects of the cellular proteome including, e.g., the turnover of protein complexes, or to address host-pathogen interactions. In combination with other pulse-labeling techniques, our analysis pipeline could also be readily expanded beyond the realm of proteins to analyze live dynamics of RNA or other biological molecules.

    Method Details

    Preparation of IgG-Coupled Dynabeads

    IgG-coupled Dynabeads were prepared essentially as described in Alber et al. (2007)
    1.
    Alber, F. ∙ Dokudovskaya, S. ∙ Veenhoff, L.M. ...
    The molecular architecture of the nuclear pore complex
    Nature. 2007; 450:695-701
    Crossref
    Scopus (861)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    . 300 mg of magnetic M-270 Epoxy coated Dynabeads (Thermo Fisher) were re-suspended in 16 mL of 0.1 M Sodium Phosphate Buffer (0.1 M Na2H/NaH2PO4 pH 7.4) and vortexed for 30 s. Fresh Antibody Mix was prepared by solubilizing 100 mg of rabbit IgG powder (Sigma-Aldrich) in 3.5 mL distilled water. Insoluble material was removed by 10 min centrifugation at 14,000 rpm in a tabletop centrifuge precooled to 4∘C. 3525 μl of the supernatant was mixed with 9.85 mL of 0.1M Sodium Phosphate Buffer, immediately followed by the addition of 6.65 mL Ammonium Sulfate Buffer (3M (NH4)2SO4 in 0.1 M Sodium Phosphate Buffer). The Antibody Mix was then filtered through a 0.22 mm Millex-GP filter (Merck Millipore). The bead suspension was washed once with 0.1 M Sodium Phosphate Buffer, supplemented with the Antibody Mix and incubated under constant agitation for ∼18 h at 30∘C. Thereafter, IgG-coupled beads were briefly washed once with 100 mM Glycine-HCl pH 2.5, 10 mM Tris-HCl pH 8.8 and 100 mM freshly prepared triethylamine. This was followed by 4 × 5 min washes with 3 mL PBS pH 7.4 and 2 × 10 min washes with 3 mL PBS pH 7.4 containing 0.5% v/v Triton X-100. Finally, the bead-solution was equilibrated with PBS pH 7.4, supplemented with 0.02% NaN3 and stored at 4∘C.

    Quantitative image analysis

    We used automated image analysis to measure the abundances and patterns formed by various NUPs at the NE. The precise specification of the method is given by the corresponding MATLAB code (see NEdetectorEO.m and Correlationextraction.m). In order to account for dark current, stray light, and other contributions that are not directly related to the presence of our labeled NUPs, image intensities are measured in background-corrected images using the top-hat transform (Soille, 2013
    67.
    Soille, P.
    Morphological Image Analysis: Principles and Applications.
    Springer Science & Business Media, 2013
    Google Scholar
    ). Candidate nuclear centers were first identified by local intensity maxima detection performed on images obtained by the difference of Gaussian method. We then identified the best circular shortest path around these candidate nuclei using dynamic programming as described e.g., in Vallotton et al. (2010)
    73.
    Vallotton, P. ∙ Sun, C. ∙ Lovell, D. ...
    DroplIT, an improved image analysis method for droplet identification in high-throughput crystallization trials
    J. Appl. Cryst. 2010; 43:1548-1552
    Crossref
    Scopus (11)
    Google Scholar
    . Dynamic programming is used to circumvent the explosion in the number of possible paths that would result if a more naive method was exploited to enumerate all possible paths. Our method identifies the best trace encircling the candidate point, where best refers to the mean intensity along the trace and to the path smoothness. After a first pass, all candidate nuclei positions are moved to the center of mass of all pixels belonging to the traces and a second tracing round is initiated. This bootstrapping procedure provides an opportunity to locate the nuclei positions more precisely and markedly improves the quality of the final traces. Only traces featuring significant Nup abundance were retained. To that end, a threshold on the total measured Nup signal along the contour was set such that spurious traces are returned by the algorithm at a frequency below 0.1%. To ensure similar abundance of newly made versus old proteins in the experiments involving RITE constructs switching from mCherry to GFP, the analyzed contours were filtered based on the background-corrected red/green intensities and only cells with red/green intensity ratios between 0.45 and 0.75 were considered for quantification. For each retained contour, we calculated the Pearson cross-correlation between background-corrected red and green fluorescence intensity. For the RITE constructs switching from no signal to GFP and GFP to no signal, non-recombining and already fully recombined cells were excluded by only considering cells with average background-corrected GFP intensities between 85 and 150. For the analysis of individual NPCs, anaphase bridges were identified in the GFP channel and then the respective signal in the corresponding mCherry channel was assessed, discriminating between overlapping and non-overlapping signal (Rajoo et al., 2018
    60.
    Rajoo, S. ∙ Vallotton, P. ∙ Onischenko, E. ...
    Stoichiometry and compositional plasticity of the yeast nuclear pore complex revealed by quantitative fluorescence microscopy
    Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA. 2018; 115:E3969-E3977
    Crossref
    Scopus (57)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    , Winey et al., 1997
    81.
    Winey, M. ∙ Yarar, D. ∙ Giddings, Jr., T.H.J. ...
    Nuclear pore complex number and distribution throughout the Saccharomyces cerevisiae cell cycle by three-dimensional reconstruction from electron micrographs of nuclear envelopes
    Mol. Biol. Cell. 1997; 8:2119-2132
    Crossref
    Scopus (185)

    ). The distribution of NUPs in the apq12Δ strains was analyzed, by qualitatively assessing distribution in the NE. Prior to analysis the images were randomized and for each NUP at least 500 cells were evaluated. Brightness and contrast of the presented micrographs was adjusted the same for all images belonging to one panel using Fiji.     Analysis of cell fitness

    Yeast strains were pre-cultured overnight in YPD at 30∘C to reach stationary phase. The cultures were diluted 1:125 in fresh YPD and growth curves were acquired in a CLARIOstar Plus automated plate reader (BMG Labtech) at 30∘C in 24-well plastic dishes (Thermo Fisher) by taking OD600 measurements every 5 min for 25 h.

    Pulse metabolic labeling

    All metabolic labeling assays were performed at 30∘C using pre-warmed culture media. Prior to the labeling onset, yeast cultures were propagated for a minimum of 16 h in synthetic complete dextrose (SCD) medium containing light l-lysine (25 mg/L). Pulse-labeling was performed at OD600 0.8-1.0 using vacuum filtration on a 0.8 μm nitrocellulose membrane to exchange light medium with heavy medium containing 13C6 15N2 l-lysine (Cambridge Isotope Laboratories, 25 mg/L). Prior to re-inoculation into heavy medium, cells were briefly washed on the filtration membrane with 50 mL of heavy l-lysine medium. Samples corresponding to the time point zero were collected immediately before the labeling onset by filtration of an equivalent of 250 mL cell culture of OD600 1.0 on a nitrocellulose membrane, briefly washed on the membrane with distilled water, and snap frozen in liquid N2. The post-labeling samples were collected in a similar manner at 30 min intervals. For the duration of the time course all cultures were maintained in log-phase in an OD range of 0.8 – 1.5 by periodical dilution with pre-warmed heavy l-lysine medium. To asses the extent of metabolic labeling due to protein intermixing during the affinity pulldown procedure log-phase yeast cultures endogenously expressing Mlp1-ZZ fusion and grown in SCD containing light l-lysine (25 mg/L) were mixed with equal amounts of the wild-type log-phase cultures propagated in 13C6 15N2 l-lysine medium for a minimum of 16 h. Cells (corresponding to 200 mL of each cell culture of OD600 1.0) were harvested as described above.

    Affinity isolation of NUP complexes

    NUP complexes were isolated according to a modified version of the NPC affinity isolation protocol described in Kim et al. (2018)
    34.
    Kim, S.J. ∙ Fernandez-Martinez, J. ∙ Nudelman, I. ...
    Integrative structure and functional anatomy of a nuclear pore complex
    Nature. 2018; 555:475-482
    Crossref
    Scopus (345)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    . All of the following procedures were performed in ice-cold conditions unless otherwise stated. Frozen yeast pellets were resuspended in 0.5 mL Lysis Buffer (20 mM HEPES pH 7.5, 50 mM KOAc, 20 mM NaCl, 2 mM MgCl2, 1 mM DTT, 10% v/v glycerol) and transferred into 2 mL screw-cap micro tubes (Sarstedt Inc) pre-filled with approximately 1 mL of 0.5 mm glass beads (Biospec products). To avoid air inclusions the tubes were spun down and filled up completely with the Lysis Buffer. Cells were lysed by four one-minute cycles at 3500 oscillations per minute in a mini-BeadBeater-24 (BioSpec Products), with 1 min cooling intermissions in ice-water mix between the cycles. Cell lysates were clarified by 30 s centrifugation at 10,000 RPM and 150 μl of supernatant was frozen in liquid N2 for later analysis of the source full cell lysates. 1 mL of the remaining supernatant was transferred to a 1.5 mL Eppendorf tube and supplemented with IgG coupled Dynabeads, pre-equilibrated with Binding Buffer (0.5% v/v Triton X-100 and 0.1% v/v Tween-20 in Lysis Buffer) and the amount of 10× detergent mastermix (protease inhibitor cocktail (Sigma-Aldrich), 5% v/v Triton x-100, 1% v/v Tween-20 in Lysis Buffer) necessary to match the detergent concentration in the binding buffer. Following 30 min incubation at 4∘C, the beads were washed twice with 1 mL of Wash Buffer (0.1% v/v Tween-20 in Lysis Buffer). Bound proteins were eluted for 2 min at 50∘C with 35 μl of 1× Laemmli sample buffer. Later, the eluates were completely denatured for 5 min at 95∘C.

    In-gel tryptic digestion

    Eluted proteins were electrophoretically concentrated by SDS-PAGE in a 4% acrylamide stacking gel. Proteins were visualized by Coomassie R-250 (Bio-Rad) staining and the excised areas were processed with a standard in-gel tryptic digestion protocol including the following essential steps: Protein disulfide bonds were reduced with dithiothreitol (6.5 mM DTT in 100 mM ammonium bicarbonate) for 1 h at 60∘C; the sample was alkylated by incubation with 54 mM iodoacetamide in 100 mM ammonium bicarbonate for 30 min in the dark at room temperature; proteins trapped in the gel matrix were digested with 1.25 μg of sequencing grade porcine trypsin (Promega) in 100 mM ammonium bicarbonate at 37∘C for 20 h; the resulting peptides were desalted in C18 BioPureSPN mini columns (The Nest Group, Inc.), eluted with Buffer B (50% acetonitrile, 0.1% formic acid) and finally recovered in 12.5 μl of Buffer A (0.1% formic acid) supplemented with 1:50 (v:v) of iRT peptides (Escher et al., 2012
    20.
    Escher, C. ∙ Reiter, L. ∙ MacLean, B. ...
    Using iRT, a normalized retention time for more targeted measurement of peptides
    Proteomics. 2012; 12:1111-1121
    Crossref
    Scopus (444)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ). The samples were transferred to MS vials for further mass-spectrometric analysis.

    Tryptic digestion of full cell lysates

    Cell lysates were adjusted to 4 mg/mL protein concentration with the Lysis Buffer (see “Affinity isolation of NUP complexes”) as determined by Bio-Rad Protein Assay (Bio-Rad) bassed on the Bradford method. Samples (typically 50 μl) were diluted with 200 μl of 7M guanidine chloride (GuHCl) in 100 mM Ammonium Bicarbonate (AmBic) to reach a final GuHCl concentration of 5.6 M. The disulfide bonds were reduced by DTT supplemented to 6.5 mM f.c. at 37∘C for 30 min and alkylated with iodoacetamide supplemented to 54 mM f.c. at 30∘C in the dark for 30 min. The samples were then diluted with 100 mM AmBic to reach a final GuHCl concentration of 1M and digested with sequencing grade porcine trypsin (Promega, 1:100 trypsin:protein) at 37∘C for 20 h. Digestion was stopped by adding 3% (v/v) of 100% formic acid (pH ∼2.0). Peptides were desalted using BioPureSPN MACRO spin columns (The Nest Group, Inc.) according to the following procedure: Cartridges were activated with one volume (200 μl) of 100% methanol, washed with two volumes of Buffer B (50% acetonitrile, 0.1% formic acid) and equilibrated with three volumes of Buffer A (0.1% formic acid). The acidified peptides were loaded twice on the cartridge, washed with three volumes Buffer A and eluted with two volumes Buffer B. Peptides were dried in a speedvac concentrator and re-solubilized in 50 μl of Buffer A. Peptide concentration was adjusted to 1 mg/mL with Buffer A based on OD280.     Mass spectrometry acquisition

    Nanoflow LC-MS/MS measurements were carried out either (i) on an EASY-nLC 1000 (Thermo Fisher) coupled to a Q Exactive Plus mass spectrometer (Thermo Fisher) equipped with a Nanospray Flex ion source or (ii) on an Acquity M-Class system (Waters) coupled to a Orbitrap Lumos mass spectrometer (Thermo Fischer) equipped with a Nanospray Flex ion source. In both cases, the peptides were separated on a 75 μm-diameter, 40 cm-long new Objective emitter packed with ReproSil-Pur C18-AQ resin (1.9 μm, Dr. Maisch) placed in a column oven at 50∘C and eluted at 300nl/min using a linear gradient of 5-to-30% Buffer A for 120min (Buffer A: 0.1% formic acid; Buffer B: 90% acetonitrile, 0.1% formic acid). Data-dependent acquisition (DDA) on the Q Exactive Plus was performed using a top20 method, with 30 s dynamic exclusion. The resolution of the Orbitrap analyzer was set to 70,000 for MS1 and 17,500 for and MS2, and the AGC target was set to 3×106 in MS1 (maximum injection time: 64 ms), and 105 in MS2 (maximum injection time: 55 ms). The mass range monitored was 350-1500 m/z in MS1 and 200-2000 m/z in MS2. MS2 acquisition was performed with a precursor isolation width of 1.4 m/z and a normalized collision energy of 25%. Data-independent acquisition (DIA) on the Q Exactive Plus used 40 fixed precursor isolation windows with 1 Da overlap (Table S2). The resolution of the Orbitrap analyzer was set to 70,000 for MS1 and 35,000 for and MS2, with AGC targets of 3×106 in MS1 (max injection time: 120 ms) and 3×106 in MS2 (maximum injection time: 60 ms). The mass range monitored was 350-1500 m/z in MS1 and was set to fixed first mass at 150 m/z in MS2. The normalized collision energy was set to HCD at 25%. Data-dependent acquisition on the Lumos was performed using the top speed mode (3 s cycle time), with 30 s dynamic exclusion. The resolution of the Orbitrap analyzer was set to 120,000 for MS1 and 30,000 for and MS2, with AGC targets of 4×105 in MS1 (max injection time: 100 ms), and 105 in MS2 (maximum injection time: 54 ms). The mass range monitored in MS1 was 350-1400 m/z and set to “first mass” at 110 m/z in MS2. MS2 acquisition was performed with a precursor isolation width of 1.6 m/z and the collision energy was set to HCD at 28%. Data-independent acquisition on the Lumos used 41 variable precursor isolation windows with 1 Da overlap (Table S2). The resolution of the Orbitrap analyzer was set to 120,000 for MS1 and 30,000 for and MS2, with AGC targets of 2×105 in MS1 (max injection time: 100 ms) and 5×105 in MS2 (maximum injection time: 50 ms). Parallel reaction monitoring on the Lumos was performed using a 1.2 Da precursor isolation width using two consecutive target lists for each sample (Table S2).     Quantification of protein labeling

    The quantification pipeline for protein labeling in KARMA assays was implemented in R (see 20200225_Mlp1_labeling.R and 20200225_10_bait_labeling.R). It includes three main steps: (1) quantification of single lysine (K1) and double lysine (K2) proteotypic precursor ion intensities; (2) selection of high-quality precursor ions; (3) computation of consensus protein labeling in K1 and K2 channels based on the respective precursor ion intensities. (1) Initially, the MS2 fragments, originating from K1 and K2 precursor ions were selected, and pre-filtered to ensure presence of all lysine residues. For example, for K2 precursors, MS2 fragments containing single or no lysine residues were excluded from the analysis. Light and Heavy precursor ion intensities were then computed as the intensity sums over the relevant MS2 fragments. The precursor ions were characterized by the same MS2 fragments across all analyzed samples. (2) The whole dataset was then split into separate KARMA experiments according to different baits each including post-labeling time series with three biological replicates per time point. Of note, zero time point samples were excluded due to lack of heavy lysine. Selection of high-quality precursor ions was carried out for each KARMA experiment separately in three consequent rounds. First, poorly detected ions, whose heavy and light species were found in less than two out of three biological replicates in any of the post-labeling time points, were discarded. This was followed by discarding data for poorly covered proteins that were represented by less than three precursor ions in any of the post-labeling samples. Lastly, noisy precursor ions were filtered out as follows: Labeling of the remaining precursor ions was computed for each KARMA sample as 𝐻/(𝐻+𝐿), where H and L are the summed intensities of the constituent heavy and light MS2 fragment ions respectively. Within each KARMA sample the precursor labeling values were further split into groups according to the protein origin. For each protein in a sample we computed median labeling value of the constituent precursors. A set of such protein’s median values obtained with a given bait for all the time points and biological replicates defined the median protein labeling profile. Analogous to this, individual precursor ions were characterized by their own labeling profiles. The MSE of the constituent precursor labeling profiles from the median was used as the filtration criterion, to exclude 50% precursor ions with the highest MSE (see Figure S1A as an example). Protein labeling was then defined based on the remaining high-quality precursor ions as 𝐻𝑡⁢𝑜⁢𝑡/(𝐻𝑡⁢𝑜⁢𝑡+𝐿𝑡⁢𝑜⁢𝑡), where 𝐻𝑡⁢𝑜⁢𝑡 and 𝐿𝑡⁢𝑜⁢𝑡 are summed intensities of the protein-born heavy and light precursor ions, respectively (Table S4). For the cell-intermixing assay (Figures S1D and S1E) we exclusively considered K1 precursor ions and excluded all ions that were not identified in at least 2 out of 4 samples. From the remaining precursor ions we only considered those with metabolic labeling values in the interquartile range 𝑄3−𝑄1 for each protein, replicate and lysis condition (see Lysintermixing_correction.R). Protein labeling was then computed as 𝐻𝑡⁢𝑜⁢𝑡/(𝐻𝑡⁢𝑜⁢𝑡+𝐿𝑡⁢𝑜⁢𝑡) (Table S4). Labeling of proteins in source cell lysates was defined based on the chromatographic peak intensities of single lysine precursor ions (Table S4) obtained with parallel reaction monitoring (see ”Analysis of mass-spectrometry data”) as 𝐻𝑡⁢𝑜⁢𝑡/(𝐻𝑡⁢𝑜⁢𝑡+𝐿𝑡⁢𝑜⁢𝑡), where 𝐻𝑡⁢𝑜⁢𝑡 and 𝐿𝑡⁢𝑜⁢𝑡 are summed intensities of heavy and light precursor ions.

    Specificity of the affinity isolation

    Analysis of NUP isolation specificity in KARMA affinity pulldowns was implemented in R (see 20200225_Specific_enrichment.R). The NUP isolation specificity was evaluated based on the MS2 fragment intensities extracted with a complementary spectral library, comprising only light lysine variants of both y- and b-type ions, from zero time point DIA datasets (ten NUP baits samples plus blank ZZ-tag samples). The ion quality filtration and intensity quantification was performed similar to as in ”Quantification of protein labeling.” The intensities of proteotypic precursor ions were determined as described in step (1) of ”Quantification of protein labeling” except that selection of K1 and K2 fragments was omitted. The high-quality precursor ions were identified as in step (2) of ”Quantification of protein labeling” except that (i) ions detected in less than 17 out of 34 samples were considered poorly detected, (ii) the exclusion limit for poorly covered proteins was set to four precursor ions per protein altogether (instead of three per sample), and (iii) filtration of noisy precursor ions was based on the fractional abundance profiles, representing precursor ion intensity values normalized for the summed value across all samples. Protein abundances were computed as in step (3) of ”Quantification of protein labeling” albeit using summed intensities of the constituent high-quality precursor ions as readouts. Protein abundances were internally (within the same sample) normalized for the abundance of the bait S-TEV-ZZ affinity tag. Abundances of missing proteins were set to zero. Normalized abundances were used as inputs for SAINTq software (Teo et al., 2016

    Similarity analysis of protein labeling

    Identification of NUP assembly groups was performed by hierarchical clustering using complete linkage function and correlation distance as a distance measure (see 20200225_Labeling_profiles_clustering.R). The correlation distance for two proteins was computed as (1−𝑟)/2, where r is a correlation coefficient for a set of the paired proteins’ labeling values across several KARMA assays. For two proteins s takes values from 0 to 1 and, therefore, protein pairs with highly correlated labeling would display low correlation distance and vice versa. Clusters of NUPs with highly correlated labeling represent signatures for assembly groups. The correlation distance matrices between all the NUP pairs, necessary for correlation clustering, were computed separately for each post-labeling time point (either 30, 60, or 90 min). The correlation distance was evaluated for every NUP pair by bootstrapping over 1,000 sub-samples each composed of 10 KARMA assays (one per bait) where for every bait the respective KARMA assay was picked at random from the three biological replicates. For calculating p values of the correlation distances we employed the same bootstrapping approach. For each protein we generated a decoy distribution of correlation distances from 100,000 sub-samples as described above, except that labeling values of a given protein were paired each time with a value of a randomly picked protein from the same KARMA assay. p values were computed as the fraction of decoy correlation distances lower than observed for a given protein pair. Since the decoy distributions were slightly different for different proteins, the correlation distance for each pair would be characterized by two slightly different p values. As the p value cutoff (<0.001, <0.01, <0.05, ≥0.05) we used the minimal of the two.

    Irreversible 2-step assembly

    In this section, we present the simplest Kinetic State Model (KSM) that describes the labeling fractions of a protein as a 2-step process. Although very simple, and having only one tunable parameter, this model captures the dynamics of most of the NUPs in our KARMA assays. In the following sections, we present solutions for more elaborate cases (such as ones with reversibility and/or more steps).
    As a simplified model, we describe the maturation of a single prey (a protein or cluster of proteins) that joins the complex at a specific well-defined point, as an irreversible process with two states.
    𝑣1→𝑆1↓𝑣2→𝑆2↓
    (1)
    The first state (𝑆1) will be denoted the maturation state, and represents all the maturation steps the prey undergoes before joining the mature complex that contains the bait. The mature state (𝑆2) represents all instances where the prey and bait are bound (either directly, or indirectly by other proteins). Obviously, the latter state also contains the fully mature complex itself (see Figure 1D).
    We assume that this system is in a balanced growth state (typical for exponentially growing cells), where all protein pools (including protein complexes and sub-complexes) are at steady state, and that protein degradation plays an insignificant role (Huang et al., 2014
    30.
    Huang, L. ∙ Kim, D. ∙ Liu, X. ...

    PLoS Comput. Biol. 2014; 10:e1003958

    Google Scholar
    ). Therefore, there is an extra dilution flux for each pool proportional to its size, where the proportionality factor is the growth rate – μ. The system of Ordinary Differential Equations (ODEs) describing the concentrations over time is:
    0=𝑑⁢𝑠1𝑑⁢𝑡=𝑣1−𝑣2−𝜇⁢𝑠1
    (2)
    0=𝑑⁢𝑠2𝑑⁢𝑡=𝑣2−𝜇⁢𝑠2
    where 𝑣1 is the rate at which the protein is synthesized, 𝑣2 is the rate of co-assembly between the prey and the bait, and 𝑠1 and 𝑠2 are the concentrations of the prey in the two corresponding states. We can thus conclude that 𝑣2=𝜇⁢𝑠2 and 𝑣1=𝜇⁢(𝑠1+𝑠2).
    The next step would be to write down the ODE system for the labeling of the two states. Unlike the total concentrations of the proteins, the labeled fractions are not assumed to be in steady-state, but rather start as completely unlabeled at time 𝑡=0 and gradually approach full labeling. We will later show how this dynamic can be described analytically (by solving the ODE system).
    First, we denote the labeling fractions, as functions of time, by: 𝑓𝑖⁡(𝑡)≡𝑠1𝑖⁡(𝑡)/(𝑠0𝑖⁡(𝑡)+𝑠1𝑖⁡(𝑡))=𝑠1𝑖⁡(𝑡)/𝑠𝑖 (where the symbols 𝑠0𝑖 and 𝑠1𝑖 are the unlabeled and labeled concentrations of 𝑆𝑖). Then:
    𝑠1⁢𝑑⁢𝑓1𝑑⁢𝑡=𝑑⁢𝑠11𝑑⁢𝑡=1⋅𝑣1−𝑓1⋅𝑣2−𝑓1⋅𝜇⁢𝑠1⁢=𝜇⋅(𝑠1+𝑠2)−𝑓1⋅(𝜇⁢𝑠1+𝜇⁢𝑠2)⁢=𝜇⋅(1−𝑓1)⋅(𝑠1+𝑠2)𝑠2⁢𝑑⁢𝑓2𝑑⁢𝑡=𝑑⁢𝑠12𝑑⁢𝑡=𝑓1⋅𝑣2−𝑓2⋅𝜇⁢𝑠2=𝜇⋅(𝑓1−𝑓2)⋅𝑠2
    (3)
    which can be simplified to:
    𝑑⁢𝑓1𝑑⁢𝑡=𝜇⋅𝑠1+𝑠2𝑠1⋅(1−𝑓1)𝑑⁢𝑓2𝑑⁢𝑡=𝜇⋅(𝑓1−𝑓2)
    (4)

    2-step assembly with reversibility

    In this section, we relax our assumption that the reaction from 𝑆1 to 𝑆2 is irreversible. Such a two-step model with reversibility can be used to describe the labeling kinetics for a dynamic protein that reversibly detaches form a bait with a certain off-rate 𝐾off. We first solve the general case where the reverse flux is an extra parameter 𝑣−2, and will later show how it applies to dynamic proteins.
    𝑣1→𝑆1↓𝑣2⇄𝑣−2𝑆2↓
    As before, we assume that the system is at balanced growth, so that the dilution fluxes are still proportional to their pool sizes, i.e., 𝜇⁢𝑠𝑖. So:
    𝑣1=𝜇⁢(𝑠1+𝑠2)𝑣2=𝜇⁢𝑠2+𝑣−2
    (10)
    Now, we can rewrite the ODE system for the labeling fractions:
    𝑠1⁢𝑑⁢𝑓1𝑑⁢𝑡=𝑑⁢𝑠11𝑑⁢𝑡=𝑣1−𝑓1⁢𝑣2−𝑓1⁢𝜇⁢𝑠1+𝑓2⁢𝑣−2⁢=𝜇⁢(𝑠1+𝑠2)−𝑓1⁢(𝜇⁢𝑠1+𝜇⁢𝑠2)+(𝑓2−𝑓1)⁢𝑣−2⁢=𝜇⁢(1−𝑓1)⁢(𝑠1+𝑠2)+(𝑓2−𝑓1)⁢𝑣−2𝑠2⁢𝑑⁢𝑓2𝑑⁢𝑡=𝑑⁢𝑠12𝑑⁢𝑡=𝑓1⁢𝑣2−𝑓2⁢𝜇⁢𝑠2−𝑓2⁢𝑣−2⁢=𝜇⁢(𝑓1−𝑓2)⁢𝑠2+(𝑓1−𝑓2)⁢𝑣−2
    (11)
    For simplicity, we define 𝑥≡𝑣−2/(𝜇⁢𝑠2) and 𝜑≡𝑠1/(𝑠1+𝑠2), therefore:
    𝑑⁢𝑓1𝑑⁢𝑡=𝜇𝜙⁢(1−𝑓1)+𝜇⁢𝑥⁢𝑠2𝑠1⁢(𝑓2−𝑓1)=𝜇𝜙⁢(1−𝑓1)+𝜇⁢𝑥⁢(1/𝜙−1)⁢(𝑓2−𝑓1)𝑑⁢𝑓2𝑑⁢𝑡=𝜇⁢(𝑓1−𝑓2)+𝜇⁢𝑥⁢(𝑓1−𝑓2)
    (12)
    Where we use that fact that 𝑠2/𝑠1=(1/𝜙−1).
    As before, we turn to matrix notation in order to solve the ODE system
    𝑑⁢→𝑓𝑑⁢𝑡=→𝑓⁢𝐌+→𝑔𝐌=𝜇⋅[−1/𝜑−𝑥⁢(1/𝜑−1)1+𝑥𝑥⁢(1/𝜑−1)−1−𝑥]⁢→𝑔=𝜇⋅[1/𝜑0]
    (13)
    and use sympy (Meurer et al., 2017

    𝑓1⁡(𝑡)=1−𝑥1+𝑥−𝜑⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡+1−𝜑1+𝑥−𝜑⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡⁢(1+𝑥)/𝜑𝑓2⁡(𝑡)=1−1+𝑥1+𝑥−𝜑⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡+𝜑1+𝑥−𝜑⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡⁢(1+𝑥)/𝜑
    (14)
    If we define 𝜑′≡𝜑/(1+𝑥), the expression for 𝑓2 can be further simplified:
    𝑓2⁡(𝑡)=1−11−𝜑′⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡+𝜑′1−𝜑′⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜑′
    (15)
    which is exactly the same form as Equation 9. In conclusion, if we can only observe the labeling of state 𝑆2, adding reversibility to the model (parameterized by x) is equivalent to reducing the EMP by a factor of 1+𝑥.
    In the case of a dynamic protein with a known 𝐾off rate, the backward flux of the protein in the KSM is given by 𝑣−2≡𝐾off⋅𝑠2. Therefore, 𝑥=𝐾off/𝜇 – i.e., the ratio between the off-rate and the cell’s growth rate – and 𝜑′ becomes 𝜑/(1+𝐾off/𝜇). The labeling kinetics of a dynamic protein would therefore completely mimic a non-dynamic protein albeit with a smaller EMP. As a consequence, very dynamic proteins would be labeled in KARMA assays indistinguishably form total cell lysates. Additionally, fitting labeling kinetic data with an irreversible KSM would always underestimate EMPs of dynamic proteins by a factor of 1+𝐾off/𝜇.
    Assuming a 90 min duplication time (i.e., 𝜇∼10−2⁢ min−1) and comparing it to the NPC off-rates measured previously for several NUPs and NTRs in mammals (Rabut et al., 2004

    ), we can conclude that the labeling kinetics of the core NUPs (𝐾off∼10−4⁢ min−1) would be mostly unaffected (less than a 1% change). At the same time, dynamic NUPs (with 𝐾off∼10−1⁢ min−1) would be labeled much faster (as if their EMP was ∼10 times smaller than it really is). The labeling of the extremely dynamic NTRs (with 𝐾off≈30⁢ min−1) would seem as if they had an insignificant EMP and thus would be virtually indistinguishable from the labeling of full cell lysates (see Figure 2F).

    Irreversible 2-step assembly with degradation

    We consider a case where the maturation state (𝑆1) undergoes protein degradation, at a rate Ω. The only change to the model would be that the dilution flux for that state (𝜇⋅𝑠1) would increase to (𝜇+Ω)⋅𝑠1 and therefore increase 𝑣1 by the same amount. The other flux (𝑣2) would remain unchanged. If we reconstruct the ODE system given this change we get:
    →𝑓≡[𝑓1𝑓2]𝐌≡𝜇⋅[−1/𝜑−Ω/𝜇10−1]→𝑔≡𝜇⋅[1/𝜑+Ω/𝜇0].
    (16)
    Therefore, one can see that, by defining 𝜑′≡(𝜑−1+Ω/𝜇)−1, we get an equivalent system to the standard case with no degradation:
    →𝑓≡[𝑓1𝑓2]𝐌≡𝜇⋅[−1/𝜑′10−1]→𝑔≡𝜇⋅[1/𝜑′0].
    (17)
    In conclusion, in cases where the maturation state undergoes protein degradation in significant rates, the effect on labeling would be equivalent to the effect of a smaller EMP or, alternatively, to a reversible model (as discussed in the previous section).

    Analytical solution for maturation time

    We define the maturation time 𝑡1/2 as the time after which a protein that starts in 𝑆1 will have a 50% chance of reaching 𝑆2. In the 2-step reversible model, the net flux from 𝑆1 to 𝑆2 is 𝜇⁢𝑠2⁢(1+𝑥), and therefore the chance of any molecule in 𝑆1 to make the transition in a short time interval 𝑑⁢𝑡 is 𝜇⁢𝑠2/𝑠1⁢(1+𝑥)⁢𝑑⁢𝑡. Furthermore, we can replace 𝑠2/𝑠1 with 1/𝜑1−1.
    We denote by 𝑃⁡(𝑡), the probability that our protein of interest has moved to 𝑆2 (matured) before time t. The chance of making the transition exactly between t and 𝑡+𝑑⁢𝑡 is the probability it did not happen already before t (which is 1−𝑃⁡(𝑡)) times the probability we just calculated earlier:
    𝑑⁢𝑃=𝑃⁡(𝑡+𝑑⁢𝑡)−𝑃⁡(𝑡)=(1−𝑃⁡(𝑡))⁢𝜇⁢𝑠2/𝑠1⁢(1+𝑥)⁢𝑑⁢𝑡∫𝑇011−𝑃𝑑𝑃=∫𝑇0𝑠2/𝑠1⁢𝜇⁢(1+𝑥)𝑑𝑡−ln⁡(1−𝑃)=𝑠2/𝑠1⁢𝜇⁢(1+𝑥)⁢𝑡=(1/𝜑−1)⁢𝜇⁢(1+𝑥)⁢𝑡𝑡=−ln⁡(1−𝑃⁡(𝑡))𝜇⁢(1+𝑥)⁢𝜑1−𝜑.
    (18)
    Now, to calculate 𝑡1/2 we simply assign 𝑃⁡(𝑡) the value of 0.5:
    𝑡1/2=−ln⁡(1−0.5)𝜇⁢(1+𝑥)⁢𝜑1−𝜑=ln⁡2𝜇⋅𝜑(1+𝑥)⁢(1−𝜑)=𝑡𝐷1+𝑥⋅𝜑1−𝜑
    (19)
    where we used the fact that doubling time (𝑡𝐷) is defined as ln⁡2/𝜇.
    Now, imagine that we fit the EMPs using data while assuming that the reactions are irreversible. In this case, we are going to underestimate φ by a factor of (1+𝑥), when trying to estimate 𝑡1/2. To understand how this assumption affects the result, we define our new estimate 𝑡′1/2 using 𝜑′ (assuming no reversibility, i.e., 𝑥′=0) and then replace 𝜑′ with 𝜑/(1+𝑥):
    𝑡′1/2≡𝑡𝐷⋅𝜑′1−𝜑′=𝑡𝐷⋅𝜑/(1+𝑥)1−𝜑/(1+𝑥)=𝑡𝐷1+𝑥⋅𝜑1−𝜑⋅1−𝜑1−𝜑/(1+𝑥)⁢=𝑡1/2⋅1−𝜑1−𝜑/(1+𝑥)
    (20)
    and since 1≥1−𝜑1−𝜑/(1+𝑥)>1−𝜑, we get that:
    1≥𝑡′1/2𝑡1/2>1−𝜑.
    (21)
    In other words, if we use an irreversible model to find the maturation time, we might underestimate it, but not by more than a factor of 1−𝜑. However, only highly dynamic proteins (i.e., with a large x value) will approach this upper bound, and we expect that this underestimation is not significant for the vast majority of NUPs.

    A 3-step process with an inaccessible state

    Whether the reaction between 𝑆1 and 𝑆2 is reversible or not, the following will always hold:
    𝑓1⁡(𝑡)≥𝑓2⁡(𝑡)
    and since we defined ⟨𝑓⟩ as the average labeled fraction, it must lie somewhere in between the two values:
    𝑓1⁡(𝑡)≥⟨𝑓⟩≥𝑓2⁡(𝑡)
    However, in some of our measurements of 𝑓2, we find that it can surpass ⟨𝑓⟩, which suggests that one of our assumptions is not true. The most likely suspect, is the assumption that the mature state (𝑆2) includes all downstream instances of the protein after its maturation (i.e., joining a complex that contains the bait).
    In order to address cases where 𝑓2>⟨𝑓⟩, we add one more state which we call the inaccessible state (and denoted 𝑆3). It represents instances of the prey which are downstream of 𝑆2, but are not accessible to affinity pulldowns and therefore do not appear in the measurement of 𝑓2. That leads to an overestimate of 𝑓2, since the inaccessible ones are likely to have a lower labeled fraction (as they are at the end of the assembly line). If 𝑠3 is large enough, it can artificially raise the value of 𝑓2 even to be higher than ⟨𝑓⟩.
    To see this effect in mathematical terms, we extended our model to have 3 irreversible steps, and use the same approach as in the 2-step model (STAR methods, “Irreversible 2-step assembly”) to solve the time-dependent labeled fractions:
    𝜇⁢(𝑠1+𝑠2+𝑠3)←→𝑆1↓𝜇⁢(𝑠2+𝑠3)←→𝑆2↓𝜇⁢𝑠3→𝑆3↓
    Note that we don’t consider the reversible case, because its solution is too complicated. The resulting ODE system is:
    𝑑⁢→𝑓𝑑⁢𝑡=→𝑓⁢𝐌+→𝑔→𝑓≡[𝑓1𝑓2𝑓3]𝐌≡𝜇⋅⎡⎢⎣−1/𝜑11/𝜑200−1/𝜑2100−1⎤⎥⎦→𝑔≡𝜇⋅[1/𝜑100]
    (22)
    where we define 𝜑1=𝑠1/(𝑠1+𝑠2+𝑠3), 𝜑2=𝑠2/(𝑠2+𝑠3). As before, we solve it using sympy (Meurer et al., 2017

    ) to get:
    𝑓1=1−𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜑1𝑓2=1−𝜑2𝜑2−𝜑1⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜑2+𝜑1𝜑2−𝜑1⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜑1𝑓3=1−𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡(1−𝜑1)⁢(1−𝜑2)+𝜑22⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜑2(𝜑2−𝜑1)⁢(1−𝜑2)−𝜑21⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜑1(𝜑2−𝜑1)⁢(1−𝜑1)

    A graphical example for the effect of the inaccessible state is shown in Figure S4C. We can conclude that 𝑓2 decreases with 𝜑1 as well as 𝜑2.

    ) for this special case, we derive the following solution (Figure S4D):
    𝑓2=1−(1+𝜇⁢𝑡𝜑2)⋅𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜑2
    (24)
    Returning to the general case, it is noteworthy, that even though 𝑓2 has two degrees of freedom (𝜑1 and 𝜑2), the function is almost redundant in parameter space, meaning that the shape of 𝑓2 is almost constant if 𝜑1⋅𝜑2=const. Figure S4E shows an example for a range of values, where 𝜑1⋅𝜑2=0.36. We also compare that to the limit 𝜑1=𝜑2=0.6 which is depicted based on Equation 24. This means, that if we try to fit these parameters to measured data, we might not be able to distinguish between a set of nearly equivalent solutions (with the same 𝜑1⋅𝜑2 value).
    In order to overcome this redundancy, we first try to fit the observed data using a model with no inaccessible state (i.e., 𝜑2=1). If adding an inaccessible state to the model (i.e., unconstraining 𝜑2) does not improve the fit in terms of RMSE, we keep the simpler 2-step model. In addition, whenever we do find that adding 𝜑2 improves the fit, we always constrain 𝜑1<𝜑2 according to the assumption that inaccessible pools are much more likely to be very small (and therefore 𝜑2 is close to 1).

    Estimating intracellular lysine turnover

    We consider a system which is devoid of any heavy lysine until time 𝑡=0, where we add isotopically labeled lysine to the media of the growing culture. Due to the finite size of what we denote as the Intracellular Lysine Pool (or ILP, which includes free lysine, tRNA-bound lysine and protein-bound lysine present in high-turnover peptides), the incorporation of heavy isotopes into newly translated NUPs is gradual, and follows the labeling fraction of the ILP, which we denote 𝜌⁡(𝑡)=1−𝑒𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓. ψ is a parameter that represents the turnover of the ILP relative to the growth rate, and depends on the ILP size and the rate of translation of stable proteins. Since we do not have reliable estimates for these values, we instead evaluated ψ by fitting labeling data obtained in our KARMA assays in a procedure described below.
    We assume that the cell is at balanced growth, with a rate of μ. Consider a protein that, after trypsin digestion, is broken down to peptides that either have a single lysine, or two lysines. For the peptides with only one lysine, the two possible labeling patterns will follow these formulae:
    𝑓(0)=𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡+∫𝑡0(1−𝜌⁡(𝜏))⁢𝜇𝑒−𝜇⁢(𝑡−𝜏)𝑑𝜏=⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡+∫𝑡0𝑒𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓⁢𝜇𝑒−𝜇⁢(𝑡−𝜏)𝑑𝜏𝑓(1)=∫𝑡0𝜌⁡(𝜏)⁢𝜇𝑒−𝜇⁢(𝑡−𝜏)𝑑𝜏=∫𝑡0(1−𝑒𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓)⁢𝜇𝑒−𝜇⁢(𝑡−𝜏)𝑑𝜏
    (25)
    note that only 𝑓(0) (the fraction of peptides with a light lysine) has a positive term before the integral, since it is equal to 1 at time 𝑡=0, while 𝑓(1) (the fraction of peptides with a heavy lysine) starts at zero.
    For peptides with exactly two lysines, the four possible labeling patterns will follow this set of formulae:
    𝑓(00)=𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡+∫𝑡0(1−𝜌⁡(𝜏))2⁢𝜇𝑒−𝜇⁢(𝑡−𝜏)𝑑𝜏⁢=𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡+∫𝑡0(𝑒2⁢𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓)⁢𝜇𝑒−𝜇⁢(𝑡−𝜏)𝑑𝜏𝑓(01)=∫𝑡0(1−𝜌⁡(𝜏))⁢𝜌⁡(𝜏)⁢𝜇𝑒−𝜇⁢(𝑡−𝜏)𝑑𝜏⁢=∫𝑡0𝑒𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓⁢(1−𝑒𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓)⁢𝜇𝑒−𝜇⁢(𝑡−𝜏)𝑑𝜏𝑓(10)=∫𝑡0𝜌⁡(𝜏)⁢(1−𝜌⁡(𝜏))⁢𝜇𝑒−𝜇⁢(𝑡−𝜏)𝑑𝜏=𝑓(01)𝑓(11)=∫𝑡0𝜌⁡(𝜏)2⁢𝜇𝑒−𝜇⁢(𝑡−𝜏)⁢𝑑⁢𝜏=∫𝑡0(1−𝑒𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓)2⁢𝜇𝑒−𝜇⁢(𝑡−𝜏)𝑑𝜏
    (26)
    We can now solve the integrals:
    𝑓(0)=𝜓𝜓−1⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓−1𝜓−1⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡𝑓(1)=1−𝜓𝜓−1⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓+1𝜓−1⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡𝑓(00)=𝜓𝜓−2⁢𝑒−2⁢𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓−2𝜓−2⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡𝑓(01)=𝑓(10)=𝜓𝜓−1⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓−𝜓𝜓−2⁢𝑒−2⁢𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓+𝜓(𝜓−1)⁢(𝜓−2)⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡𝑓(11)=1−2⁢𝜓𝜓−1⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓+𝜓𝜓−2⁢𝑒−2⁢𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓−2(𝜓−1)⁢(𝜓−2)⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡
    (27)
    This solution is not defined for 𝜓=1 or 𝜓=2, but since we expect the value of this parameter to be way below 1, we avoid such cases by constraining 𝜓<1.
    In our current KARMA pipeline, the two channels can measure 𝑓(0), 𝑓(1), 𝑓(00), and 𝑓(11), and only in relative terms. Therefore, we define 𝐾1 and 𝐾2 as the relative values:
    𝐾1=𝑓(1)𝑓(0)+𝑓(1)=𝑓(1)=1−𝜓⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓−𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡𝜓−1𝐾2=𝑓(11)𝑓(00)+𝑓(11)⁢=(𝜓−1)⁢(𝜓−2)−2⁢𝜓⁢(𝜓−2)⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓+𝜓⁢(𝜓−1)⁢𝑒−2⁢𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓−2⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡(𝜓−1)⁢(𝜓−2)−2⁢𝜓⁢(𝜓−2)⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓+2⁢𝜓⁢(𝜓−1)⁢𝑒−2⁢𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓−2⁢𝜓⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡
    (28)
    Solving for 𝐾2 as a function of 𝐾1 is probably not possible analytically, but we can easily plot the function for several values of ψ, as shown in Figure S4H.
    Therefore, given a value of ψ, we can calculate the standardized Euclidean distance (i.e., the Euclidean distance normalize by standard error) to each of the data points by minimizing the distance to the 𝐾1-𝐾2 curve predicted by the model. The mean of all distances represents how well the model fits the data. After trying a range of ψ values, we find that the optimal ψ is equal to 0.35.

    Solution for labeling of preys in KARMA

    After estimating the Intracellular Lysine Pool parameter ψ, we move on to fit a KSM for the NUP baits, which is based on a 4-step model:
    𝑣𝑙⁢𝑦⁢𝑠⟶𝑆𝑙⁢𝑦⁢𝑠↓𝑣1→𝑆1↓𝑣2→𝑆2↓𝑣3→𝑆3↓
    Let 𝑠𝑖 be the concentration associated with state 𝑆𝑖. At balanced growth conditions, the fluxes obey the following equations:
    𝑣1=𝜇⁢(𝑠1+𝑠2+𝑠3)𝑣2=𝜇⁢(𝑠2+𝑠3)𝑣3=𝜇𝑠3
    (29)
    Note that 𝑣𝑙⁢𝑦⁢𝑠 does not obey a similar equation, since lysine is used in many other protein synthesis reactions, and the dilution by growth is probably negligible compared to that. Fortunately, we do not need to estimate 𝑣𝑙⁢𝑦⁢𝑠 since (as we will see below) the ILP parameter ψ can be used instead.
    Compared to the 2-step model (STAR methods, “Irreversible 2-step assembly”), we have two extra states (besides the maturation state 𝑆1 and mature state 𝑆2). The first is the Intracellular Lysine Pool (𝑆𝑙⁢𝑦⁢𝑠) which we have dealt with in the previous section, and an inaccessible state 𝑆3 which we add to deal with baits that are labeled quickly.
    The 𝐾1 data in the KARMA assays represents the labeled fraction of mature states 𝑆2. Let →𝑓≡[𝑓𝑙⁢𝑦⁢𝑠𝑓1𝑓2𝑓3] be the vector of all labeled fractions (of the 4 states). The change in →𝑓 is described by the following ODE:
    𝑑⁢→𝑓𝑑⁢𝑡=→𝑓⁢𝐌+→𝑔𝐌≡⎡⎢⎣−𝑣𝑙⁢𝑦⁢𝑠/𝑠𝑙⁢𝑦⁢𝑠𝑣1/𝑠1000−𝑣1/𝑠1𝑣2/𝑠2000−𝑣2/𝑠2𝑣3/𝑠3000−𝑣3/𝑠3⎤⎥⎦→𝑔≡[𝑣𝑙⁢𝑦⁢𝑠/𝑠𝑙⁢𝑦⁢𝑠000]
    (30)
    Now, we define 𝜓≡𝑠𝑙⁢𝑦⁢𝑠⁢𝜇/𝑣𝑙⁢𝑦⁢𝑠, 𝜑1≡𝑠1/(𝑠1+𝑠2+𝑠3)=𝑠1⁢𝜇/𝑣1, and 𝜑2≡𝑠2/(𝑠2+𝑠3)=𝑠2⁢𝜇/𝑣2. So we can rewrite the system as:
    𝐌≡𝜇⋅⎡⎢⎣−1/𝜓1/𝜑1000−1/𝜑11/𝜑2000−1/𝜑21000−1⎤⎥⎦→𝑔≡𝜇⁢[1/𝜓000]
    As in Equation 8, the solution to the ODE system (when →𝑓⁡(0)=→0 and →𝑔=const) is:
    →𝑓⁡(𝑡)=→𝑔⋅𝐌−1⁢(𝑒𝐌⁢𝑡−𝐈)
    (31)
    Assigning the values for 𝐌 and →𝑔 we get:
    →𝑓=1−[1111]⋅exp⁡⎛⎜⎝⎡⎢⎣−1/𝜓1/𝜑1000−1/𝜑11/𝜑2000−1/𝜑21000−1⎤⎥⎦⁢𝜇⁢t⎞⎟⎠
    (32)
    Even though we can continue to derive a closed-form formula for 𝑓2, there are some advantages to using the matrix form. First, it is more compact, especially when the labeling of the other states are needed as well. Second, explicitly laying out the solution to the exponent of 𝐌 requires handling a few singularities (e.g., when ψ, 𝜑1, and 𝜑2 have non-distinct values). Finally, it is easier to extend by adding more intermediate steps when needed. In our KARMA implementation, we use the scipy.linalg.expm (Virtanen et al., 2020
    75.
