    ) function to calculate the matrix exponent numerically.

    Internal standard for KSM based on NTRs

    We now have an expression for the labeling of the mature state as a function of time (and two parameters 𝜑1 and 𝜑2). However, due to the way the protein samples are extracted, it is difficult to have a precise time estimate for our KARMA assay samples. Furthermore, relying on the sampling time (and the effective growth rate of the cell culture) for calculating the value of the expected biomass increase (𝑒𝜇⁢𝑡) requires absorbance measurements which are themselves error prone, and in addition complicate our experimental setup. Instead, we sought to use the labeling data itself as an internal standard in order to estimate the value of 𝑒𝜇⁢𝑡 for each sample. We thus carefully selected proteins that represent the average labeling of the entire protein pool, supported by the fact that their labeling fraction at each time point did not depend on the bait, and closely matched their labeling fraction in the crude extract. In this way, we identified three internal reference proteins: Mex67, Kap95, and Kap123 (see Figure S4I). These reference proteins bind to the NPC in an extremely highly dynamic manner completely intermixing between the bound and the unbound states. Therefore, whatever the EMP φ is, the effective 𝜑′ (STAR methods, “2-step assembly with reversibility”) will be close to 0. In addition, due to their dynamic nature, we assume that NTRs do not have an inaccessible state. Under these assumptions, the labeling of NTRs should follow the following equation (see Figure S4I):
    𝑓2=1−11−𝜓⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡+𝜓1−𝜓⁢𝑒−𝜇⁢𝑡/𝜓
    (33)
    Using the fitted value for ψ and the collected data, we can solve for t and take the average across the three internal reference proteins. Since the inverse function does not have a closed-form analytical solution, it must be solved numerically (here, we used the pynverse package).
    We were interested in comparing our time estimates (from the internal reference proteins) with direct measurements of biomass (by absorbance at 600nm). Unlike the data used for fitting ψ, which consisted only of 3 time points, here we measured the OD and purified protein samples from five time-points (30, 60, 90, 120, and 150 min), but only using one of the affinity handles – Mlp1. As expected, one can appreciate that the labeling significantly lags behind the biomass growth (red versus blue lines in Figure S4I). After calculating the values for t, i.e., using the inverse of 𝑓2 in Equation 33, we compared the measured relative biomass increase (based on the OD measurements) to the expected increased based on the calculated time and the growth rate (Figure S4J). Notably, the first two OD measurements seem to underestimate the biomass growth. This discrepancy might be explained by the fast dynamics of the label at the start of the experiment, and the fact that protein extraction and affinity pull-downs cannot be done instantaneously. We decided to rely more heavily on the time estimates calculated using the labeling of the reference proteins, rather than biomass measurements which are more error prone and might have systematic biases due to the need to dilute the growing culture throughout the experiment. Another reason to use the labeling is that it is an intrinsic observation taken from the exact same sample as the analyzed data and using the same proteomic pipeline.
    The method of using reference proteins as internal standards for KSM can have multiple applications beyond KARMA. Any dynamic labeling experiment requires fitting an ODE system which aims to describe the labeling as a function of time. Transforming it into a function of another intrinsic value measured together with the target labeling fraction bypasses many sources of noise and increases the robustness of the fit.

    KSM for each bait/prey based on labeling

    Finally, we apply the following procedure in order to fit a KSM for all our 320 KARMA assay results, i.e., 32 NUP preys × 10 baits. For each bait, the median among the reference protein labeling values is used as estimate the effective sampling time (for each time point and replicate). These values are used together with the corresponding NUP prey labeling data in our EMP estimation procedure, which is based on the KSM model as in the STAR Methods, “Irreversible 2-step assembly.” For 44 out of the 320 pairs, we find that the average labeling of the prey is higher than the average among the reference proteins. Our standard KSM model cannot explain such data (the fastest labeling possible is for 𝜑1=0, and therefore the reference proteins are already at that maximum). In these cases, we fit a KSM with 4-steps, by adding an inaccessible state (and an extra parameter 𝜑2) as explained in the STAR Methods, “A 3-step process with an inaccessible state.” To avoid the observability problem, we use transformed parameters instead of 𝜑1 and 𝜑2 directly in the optimization: 𝑥=𝜑1⁢𝜑2 and 𝑧=(1−𝜑1⁢𝜑−12)/(1−𝜑1⁢𝜑2). Note that z represents the extent of how close 𝜑2 is to 𝜑1, in a scale between 0 and 1, i.e., when 𝜑2=𝜑1 then 𝑧=0 and when 𝜑2=1 then 𝑧=1. Both x and z are constrained to the range (0,1). After fitting the labeling data, we use the following formulae to get the relative state sizes:
    𝜑1=√𝑥⁢(1−𝑧+𝑧⁢𝑥)𝜑2=√𝑥/(1−𝑧+𝑧⁢𝑥)
    For all KSM fits, we use the Trust Region Reflective algorithm implemented by scipy.optimize.curve_fit (Virtanen et al., 2020
    75.
    Virtanen, P. ∙ Gommers, R. ∙ Oliphant, T.E. ..., SciPy 1.0 Contributors
    SciPy 1.0: fundamental algorithms for scientific computing in Python
    Nat. Methods. 2020; 17:261-272
    Crossref
    Scopus (18328)
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ). This function provides a co-variance matrix along with the optimum, by calculating the inverse of the Hessian matrix at the optimal point. The diagonal values represent the variance in each single optimization variable. Our uncertainty estimate for 𝜑1 are based on the square root of the variance associated with the first parameter (𝜑1 in most cases, or x in the cases where an inaccessible pool was added).
    A schematic overview of the process is shown in Figure S5A. In addition, we show two examples for our KSM fit (one of which requires an inaccessible state) in Figures S5B and S5C.

    Maturation sequence of NPC biogenesis

    After fitting the EMP fractions using a KSM for each of the assembly groups and with respect to the different baits, we moved on to elucidate the sequence of maturation steps using a binary tree model (Gamalinda and Woolford, 2015
    23.
    Gamalinda, M. ∙ Woolford, Jr., J.L.
    Paradigms of ribosome synthesis: Lessons learned from ribosomal proteins
    Translation (Austin). 2015; 3:e975018
    PubMed
    Google Scholar
    ). Our approach was to iterate through all possible orders of maturation, where each order can be represented by a binary tree whose leaves are the 9 clusters. Each leaf and each vertex (i.e., a mature complex of several such leaves) in the tree is assigned a single variable which represents its relative pool size. This set of variables is then optimized to match the EMP data from the KSM fitting (Figure 5A and STAR methods, “Fitting Effective Maturation Pools”). Finally, we select the top 0.1% of trees that have the best match to the KSM data, and analyze the level distribution in order to estimate the sequence of maturation steps.

    Tree generating procedure

    We considered all possible binary trees with n distinct leaves, and discard all isomorphisms (i.e., trees that can be shown to be equivalent by a series of branch rotations). To generate these trees, we used the following recursion (Figure S5E):
    •
    Let 𝐸⁢(𝑛−1) be a set of all trees with 𝑛−1 leaves
    •
    For each tree in 𝐸⁢(𝑛−1) and for each vertex in the tree (both branch points and leaves):
    –
    Append the new leaf (n) to the right of the chosen vertex, by adding a branch point and moving the original sub-tree to the left branch (see Figure S5E).
    –
    Add the new tree to the next set of trees 𝐸⁡(𝑛)
    This procedure avoids creating isomorphic trees, since we always add the new leaf to the right branch. Therefore, for any sub-tree, the leaf with the highest value is always on the right – i.e., the leaves are in lexicographic order. That makes it a unique tree for each isomorphism class.
    This procedure also makes it easy for us to count the number of trees. First, we note that any binary tree with 𝑛−1 leaves has 𝑛−2 non-terminal vertices. So, every tree in 𝐸⁢(𝑛−1) has exactly 2⁢𝑛−3 vertices and in each step of the recursion, we multiply the number of trees by this number. Obviously, 𝐸⁡(1)=1, so the general formula is:
    𝐸⁡(𝑛)=𝐸⁡(𝑛−1)⋅(2⁢𝑛−3)=…=𝐸⁡(1)⋅1⋅3⋅5⋅…⋅(2⁢𝑛−3)⁢=∏𝑖=2𝑛(2⁢𝑖−3)
    (34)
    Here are the values if 𝐸⁡(𝑛) for 𝑛≤9:

    Fitting Effective Maturation Pools

    Since we grouped the preys into 9 clusters, we only need to consider the 𝐸⁡(9)=2,027,025 possible binary trees. To score each tree, we assigned an abundance value to each vertex within the tree (8 branch points and 9 leaves). To calculate the EMP of a cluster-bait pair, we first identify all vertices that contain the prey cluster by following the direct path from the leaf up to the root (Figure 5A). We then calculate two values: (i) the sum of all corresponding abundance values on this path, and (ii) the sum of only those vertices that are below the branch point where the prey cluster and bait co-assemble. The EMP is the ratio between these two sums (Figure 5A). Finally, we fit the abundance values of an entire tree, by minimizing the RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error) between the computed EMPs from the binary tree and the ones estimated by the KSM (Figure 5A). For finding the global optimum, we used scipy.optimize.minimize (Virtanen et al., 2020
    75.

    ) with several random initial values and checked for convergence.

    Contribution of AP intermixing

    Following cell lysis and throughout the affinity purification step, protein species can exchange between the different pools. The faster this intermixing is, the closer the labeling of the observed (post-AP) protein would be to the whole-cell lysate values. To test the robustness of our maturation kinetic model to such protein intermixing bias, we re-analyzed the NPC maturation sequence using prey labeling values that were corrected for this effect, as explained below.
    In full lysates, before the AP step, measuring the labeling fraction of any given prey protein would yield approximately the same value – i.e., the labeling of the entire protein pool. As explained in section “Internal standard for KSM based on NTRs,” we use the labeling of the NTR proteins as a proxy to the full lyastes, denoted by 𝑓𝑁⁢𝑇⁢𝑅. On the other hand, at the moment each sample is taken, the labeling of the prey in the mature pool (i.e., bound to the bait) would typically have different value – 𝑓∗ – and is described by our KSM. The effect of intermixing, is that the observed labeling of the prey in the AP – denoted f – would be somewhere in between 𝑓∗ (no intermixing) and 𝑓𝑁⁢𝑇⁢𝑅 (complete intermixing). Since all APs were conducted using the same protocol, we can reasonably assume that there is a constant intermixing factor (α) that depends on the nature of the prey protein and determines the fraction of prey molecules which is exchanged during the AP step. Thus:
    𝑓=(1−𝛼)⋅𝑓∗+𝛼⋅𝑓𝑁⁢𝑇⁢𝑅
    (35)
    To determine the value of α, we use the results of our culture-mixing tests (see “Pulse metabolic labeling” section), where fully labeled wild-type cells were mixed with unlabeled cells expressing ZZ-tagged Mlp1 in a 1:1 ratio and subjected to AP as in KARMA. Without any intermixing, the observed protein labeling would be zero. On the other hand, if the pools would mix completely, the labeling would be 0.5. We mark the observed labeling of the AP pull-downs in these intermixing tests by 𝑓𝑚⁢𝑖⁢𝑥, which would again be a weighted average between the pre-mixed labeling and the equilibrium state weighed by α, i.e.
    𝑓𝑚⁢𝑖⁢𝑥=(1−𝛼)⋅0+𝛼⋅0.5
    (36)
    and therefore 𝛼=2⋅𝑓𝑚⁢𝑖⁢𝑥. Combining Equations 35 and 36 we get:
    𝑓∗=𝑓−2⁢𝑓𝑚⁢𝑖⁢𝑥⁢𝑓𝑁⁢𝑇⁢𝑅1−2⁢𝑓𝑚⁢𝑖⁢𝑥
    (37)
    The corrected labeling values 𝑓∗ were used as inputs to parametrize the KSM and evaluate the NPC maturation order as described in the above sections. If the effect of intermixing was substantial, the results based on the corrected values would differ significantly from the uncorrected ones. The resulting maturation sequence is presented in the Figures S5H and S5I.

    Strictly Necessary Cookies

    Always active

    These cookies are necessary for the website to function and cannot be switched off in our systems. They are usually only set in response to actions made by you which amount to a request for services, such as setting your privacy preferences, logging in or filling in forms. You can set your browser to block or alert you about these cookies, but some parts of the site will not then work. These cookies do not store any personally identifiable information.

    Functional Cookies

    These cookies enable the website to provide enhanced functionality and personalisation. They may be set by us or by third party providers whose services we have added to our pages. If you do not allow these cookies then some or all of these services may not function properly.

    Performance Cookies

    These cookies allow us to count visits and traffic sources so we can measure and improve the performance of our site. They help us to know which pages are the most and least popular and see how visitors move around the site.

    Targeting Cookies

    These cookies may be set through our site by our advertising partners. They may be used by those companies to build a profile of your interests and show you relevant adverts on other sites. If you do not allow these cookies, you will experience less targeted advertising.
